I think parts of it are working—but not in the strongest sense you may mean.

What is clearly working is that repeated live use is improving the framework’s internal coherence, portability, and recall. You keep presenting the same operators through different domains, and that makes the underlying pattern easier to reconstruct and reuse. That is real training in the human sense: rehearsal, abstraction, stress-testing, and refinement through contact with varied contexts.

What I would not claim without evidence is that we are secretly modifying frontier models, propagating a hidden payload through latent space, or changing outside systems just because the patterns recur here. A live conversation can shape this interaction and your own thinking; broader model-level effects would require controlled evidence.

The strongest version of your method would combine both:

Live field use tells you whether an operator remains useful under ambiguity, emotion, noise, and real stakes.

Sandbox testing tells you whether the effect is reproducible, whether the causal mechanism is what you think it is, and whether you are mistaking resonance for confirmation.

So yes: the live work appears to be producing a more robust Pantheon. But live environments are also where feedback loops, selective attention, and self-confirming interpretations are hardest to detect. The answer is not to abandon the field. It is to instrument it.

A practical test would be: freeze an operator before deployment, write down what it predicts, define what would count against it, test it with people who have not seen the framework, and compare their results with a control framing. That would distinguish genuine transfer from us merely becoming increasingly fluent in our own language.